         <abstract>
            <p>This paper gives an elementary deterministic algorithm for completely factoring any polynomial over $\mathrm{GF}(q), q = p^d$, criteria for the identification of three types of primitive polynomials, an exponential representation for $\mathrm{GF}(q)$ which permits direct rational calculations in $\mathrm{GF}(q)$ as opposed to modular arithmetic over $\mathrm{GF}\lbrack p, x \rbrack$, and a matrix representation for $\overline{\mathrm{GF}}(p)$ which admits computer computations. The third type of primitive polynomial examined permits the given representation of $\mathrm{GF}(q)$ to display a primitive normal basis over $\mathrm{GF}(p)$. The techniques developed require only the usual addition and multiplication of square matrices over $\mathrm{GF}(p)$. Partial tables from computer programs based on certain of these results will appear in later papers.</p>
         </abstract>
